  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, USA)\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a criminal activity\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n\n2. 1980s Developments\n- Introduction of anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Increased financial reporting requirements\n- Growing international cooperation\n\n3. Key Milestone: FATF Establishment (1989)\n- Created global standards for combating money laundering\n- Developed 40 recommendations for comprehensive AML strategies\n- Encouraged international collaboration\n\n4. Post-9/11 Legislation\n- Patriot Act (2001, USA)\n- Enhanced financial transparency\n- Stricter regulations on international financial transactions\n- Expanded scope to include terrorist financing\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- More sophisticated risk assessment techniques\n\n6. Global Regulatory Frameworks\n- EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Enhanced Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Cross-border information sharing\n\nThe legislation continues to adapt to emerging financial technologies and criminal techniques.",
